To add an intent to a button that opens a popup at the bottom of the screen for sharing, you can follow these steps:

1. First, make sure you have a button element defined in your app's layout XML file. For example, you can use a `Button` with an id:
```xml
<Button
    android:id="@+id/shareButton"
    android:layout_width="wrap_content"
    android:layout_height="wrap_content"
    android:text="Share"
    />
```

2. In your app's activity (e.g., `MainActivity.java`), find the button by its id and set an `OnClickListener` to handle the click event:
```java
Button shareButton = findViewById(R.id.shareButton);
shareButton.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    @Override
    public void onClick(View v) {
        // Handle button click here
    }
});
```

3. Inside the `onClick()` method, create an `Intent` to share the content. You can use the `Intent.ACTION_SEND` action and provide the content to be shared using the `Intent.EXTRA_TEXT` extra. For example, to share a text message:
```java
String shareBody = "Content to be shared";
Intent shareIntent = new Intent(Intent.ACTION_SEND);
shareIntent.setType("text/plain");
shareIntent.putExtra(Intent.EXTRA_TEXT, shareBody);
```

4. To narrow down the sharing options to only messaging apps, you can create a chooser based on the `Intent` and set its title. Additionally, you can set the package name of the default SMS/MMS app using the `Intent.EXTRA_PACKAGE_NAME` extra:
```java
Intent smsIntent = new Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW);
smsIntent.setData(Uri.parse("sms:"));
Intent chooserIntent = Intent.createChooser(shareIntent, "Share via");
chooserIntent.putExtra(Intent.EXTRA_INITIAL_INTENTS, new Intent[] { smsIntent });
```
Note: By default, this will include all the installed messaging apps on the device as available options. The `smsIntent` helps include the default messaging app in the chooser.

5. Finally, start the activity with the created `chooserIntent`:
```java
startActivity(chooserIntent);
```

That's it! Now, when the button is clicked, a popup will appear at the bottom of the screen containing available messaging apps to share the content.

To add a `TextWatcher` implementation to an `EditText`, you can use the `addTextChangedListener()` method. It allows you to register a `TextWatcher` object to monitor changes in the text input of the `EditText`. Here's an example:

1. Create a `TextWatcher` implementation:
```kotlin
val textWatcher = object : TextWatcher {
    override fun beforeTextChanged(s: CharSequence?, start: Int, count: Int, after: Int) {
        // Executed before the text is changed
    }

    override fun onTextChanged(s: CharSequence?, start: Int, before: Int, count: Int) {
        // Executed while the text is being changed

        // Access the updated text using s.toString()
        val updatedText = s.toString()

        // Implement your desired logic here, based on the updated text
    }

    override fun afterTextChanged(s: Editable?) {
        // Executed after the text has been changed
    }
}
```

In the above example, we create an anonymous object that implements the `TextWatcher` interface. Based on your requirements, you can define your logic inside the `onTextChanged()` method.

2. Attach the `TextWatcher` to the `EditText`:
```kotlin
val myEditText = findViewById<EditText>(R.id.myEditText)
myEditText.addTextChangedListener(textWatcher)
```

Here, we fetch the `EditText` using its id, `myEditText`, using `findViewById()`. Then, we call `addTextChangedListener()` on the `myEditText` object and pass our `textWatcher` implementation as an argument.

With this implementation, the `textWatcher` will monitor any changes made to the text in the `EditText`, providing you with hooks to perform custom logic during different stages of the text change process.
